This is a textbook case of **"coverage without verification"** — every method is exercised, but almost nothing is actually asserted. Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## 🔴 Critical — Assert-Free Tests (fire-and-forget)

These tests call production code but **assert nothing**, so any bug passes silently.

**1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)** — No assertion that the product was persisted.
```csharp
// Fix: assert the product is retrievable after adding
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
Assert.AreEqual(product, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

**2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)** — Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the new price.
```csharp
// Fix: verify the price actually changed
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

**3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)** — Calls `RemoveProduct` but never checks deletion.
```csharp
// Fix: verify the product is gone
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

**4. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)** — No data added, count not asserted. Always passes.
```csharp
// Fix: add products, assert count
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
```

**5. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)** — Discount applied but no price verified. A broken formula (e.g. `Price * fraction` instead of `Price * (1 - fraction)`) would pass.
```csharp
// Fix: verify resulting prices
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

**6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 85)** — Imports a line but never checks any product was created.
```csharp
// Fix: verify the imported product
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var p = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(p);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", p!.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, p.Price);
```

---

## 🟠 High — Weak Assertions (`IsNotNull` on guaranteed non-null)

These have an `Assert.IsNotNull` that can never fail given the production code, masking real bugs.

**7. `GetProduct_Works` (line 25)** — Asserts not-null but never checks the returned **values**.
```csharp
// Fix: verify returned data matches what was stored
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result!.Name);
